	 - From TAT: The paragraphs from the African Times news article provide several details that support the claim regarding Mr. Ussher's lack of genuine authority or willingness to enforce British rule. Firstly, it is noted that Mr. Ussher was aware of the Cape Coast people's intention to join the Fantee army, as they had publicly announced their plans days in advance. Despite this, he did not take any preventive action, suggesting a reluctance or inability to enforce British authority. Furthermore, Mr. Ussher's private statement to his friends, advising that the people should go to the camp discreetly so he would not be compelled to stop them, directly aligns with the claim that he preferred the people to act discreetly rather than openly. This indicates a lack of genuine authority or willingness to confront the situation head-on. Additionally, the article describes how Mr. Ussher's actions, such as ordering the destruction of Attah's house, were reactive and seemingly ineffective, as they occurred after the Cape Coast men had already joined the Fantee army. These observations collectively suggest that Mr. Ussher's actions were more about managing appearances than exerting real control, thus supporting the claim.


